mille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Liz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from Liz in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). As a Hispanic name it may also be an altered form of   Lis  . Compare   Deliz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Stanislaw, Wladyslaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignatius, Malgorzata, Slawomir, Tadeusz, Tomasz, Boleslaw, Bronislaw, Darek.","Polish, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish and Czech dialect <i>lis</i> ‘fox’, Upper Sorbian <i>lis</i> ‘he-fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name. The presumably cognate Sorbian surname <b>Liš</b> is found in Germanized and probably also Americanized forms, only (see   Liesch   and   Lish  ). Compare also   Lese  ,   Lies  , and   Liss  .","Czech: nickname for a man with a bald pate, from a variant of the adjective <i>lysý</i> ‘bald’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William St Liz was born about 1274, in Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Sir Richard de Senlis, was 32 and his mother, Matilda, was 35. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Anne. He died in 1313, in Duddington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1274–1313":"umbes 1274–1313","1274–1313":"1274–1313","1279–1300":"1279–1300","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1243–1286":"1243–1286","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1286":"1286","1264":"1264","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","Abt 1274":"umbes 1274","1313":"1313","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1298":"umbes 1298","1243":"1243","1298":"1298","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","Huddington, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Duddington, Northamptonshire, England":"Duddington, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1274–1313":"noin 1274–1313","1274–1313":"1274–1313","1279–1300":"1279–1300","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1300–1374":"1300–1374","1243–1286":"1243–1286","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1286":"1286","1264":"1264","1374"